Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
I=E2=80=99ve become obsessed with a certain kind of company recently. This =
is my attempt to put a framework around the opportunity.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Techno-Industrial Revolution
We=E2=80=99re standing at the foot of a Techno-Industrial Revolution.=C2=A0
Progress shifted from atoms to bits and is now shifting to a combination of=
 atoms and bits.=C2=A0
In Tech is Going to Get Much Bigger [ https://substack.com/redirect/5cf5dd3=
4-099d-48ec-9d5d-a50ce29fae5e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I argued that cheaper energy, intelligence, and de=
xterity (i.e. robots), and I would add biotech and new materials to the lis=
t, will combine to increase tech=E2=80=99s total addressable market to incl=
ude large existing industries that have been relatively untouched by techno=
logy, including industrials and agriculture. Higher margins in large indust=
ries will make for very valuable companies.=C2=A0=C2=A0
These companies will look less like the tech giants of today and more like =
the giants of the Industrial Revolution.=C2=A0
Some, certainly, will be the incumbents that take advantage of cheaper, mor=
e capable inputs to improve their businesses. Think Adobe incorporating AI =
or a factory installing robots. Cheaper, more capable inputs, in many cases=
, will be a rising tide that lifts all boats. Clayton Christensen would cal=
l these sustaining innovations.
But I also believe that there will be a crop of new companies that challeng=
e incumbents head-on and win, capturing large markets at high margins in th=
e process. I=E2=80=99ve started calling them Techno-Industrials.
Techno-Industrials use technology to build atoms-based products with struct=
urally superior unit economics with the ultimate goal of winning on cost in=
 large existing markets, or expanding or creating new markets where there i=
s pent-up demand.=C2=A0
They can leverage their structurally superior unit economics in the form of=
 lower prices to win market share, higher gross margins, or both.=C2=A0
Less fancily, they=E2=80=99ll use new technology, processes, or approaches =
to make physical things that customers want more cheaply than existing comp=
anies can, in a way that existing companies can=E2=80=99t match. Because th=
ey can manufacture more cheaply, they can either lower their prices to stea=
l market share from incumbents or capture more gross margin. In some cases,=
