Aggregators and Industrials=C2=A0
Anduril, Solugen, and Monumental Labs are just three examples, and all thre=
e are still relatively early in the journey. Most of the promise of Techno-=
Industrials as it stands lies in spreadsheets and techno-economic analyses =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/0e4e2f45-7a3c-4403-b27f-43b2c1c8fb86?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
A skeptic would argue that we=E2=80=99ve heard this story before. In the 20=
10s, companies that dealt in the physical world promised better margins thr=
ough technology.=C2=A0
Companies like WeWork, Bird, and my company, Breather, failed to live up to=
 that promise.=C2=A0
Ultimately, while they were tech-enabled, the technology wasn=E2=80=99t inf=
used into the product in such a way that they changed the cost physics of t=
heir industries.=C2=A0
From an economic perspective, it was like squeezing a money balloon: we jus=
t shifted dollars from one side to the other.
There are also a number of successes. DoorDash is worth $42 billion. Airbnb=
 is worth $89 billion. Uber is worth $134 billion.=C2=A0
I would argue that these companies didn=E2=80=99t change the cost physics o=
f their industries, either. Food is not cheaper. Travel is not cheaper. Cat=
ching a ride is not cheaper.=C2=A0
These companies are examples of what Ben Thompson famously calls Aggregator=
s [ https://substack.com/redirect/a09feaa2-d1f2-4f9d-bd5f-8935104c1ddd?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
Aggregators =E2=80=9Caggregate modularized suppliers =E2=80=94 which they o=
ften don=E2=80=99t pay for =E2=80=94 to consumers/users with whom they have=
 an exclusive relationship at scale.=E2=80=9D
These companies do create value. There=E2=80=99s value in convenience, and =
there=E2=80=99s value in being able to monetize an underutilized resource, =
whether that=E2=80=99s an empty house or an hour of time. But they don=E2=
=80=99t structurally improve the gross margins on the products in their mar=
kets. They don=E2=80=99t change the cost physics. Like the balloon squeezer=
, they just move them from one place to another.=C2=A0
One of the key ideas behind Aggregation Theory is Clayton Christensen=E2=80=
=99s Law of Conservation of Attractive Profits. Note the word conservation.=
 Aggregators didn=E2=80=99t expand industries=E2=80=99 profits as much as t=
hey moved them from one place to another.=C2=A0
Reasoning about Techno-Industrials requires us to go back further in time, =
all the way back to the Industrial Revolution in America. I=E2=80=99m calli=
ng this coming stage the Techno-Industrial Revolution, but the Industrial R=
evolution was a techno-industrial revolution, too.=C2=A0
Companies like ALCOA and Carnegie Steel invented or leveraged new technolog=
y to atoms-based products with structurally superior unit economics with th=
e ultimate goal of winning on cost in large existing markets, or expanding =
or creating new markets where there is pent-up demand.=C2=A0
Take ALCOA. In 1880, before Charles Martin Hall and Paul H=C3=A9roult indep=
endently invented what became known as the Hall-H=C3=A9roult Process for al=
uminum smelting, the metal sold for $17 per pound. In 1884, the US only pro=
duced 125 pounds of aluminum, at least 100 ounces of which went to the caps=
tone of the newly built Washington Monument, the tallest structure in the w=
orld.=C2=A0
In 1903, the Wright Brothers built the engine for their historic plane usin=
g aluminum alloy. By 1930, aluminum sold for $0.20 per pound and ALCOA was =
responsible [ https://substack.com/redirect/2c78f83d-a252-4a7b-a03c-b2ad989=
d734d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for over half of worldwide aluminum capacity. The US alone produced 148,000=
 tons of the metal in 1939. When Sputnik launched in 1957, it brought its a=
luminum body into orbit. Today, it=E2=80=99s impossible to imagine the worl=
d without the lightweight, flexible metal and its alloys.=C2=A0=C2=A0
ALCOA dominated the industry so handily that in 1938, FDR=E2=80=99s Justice=
 Department sued it for antitrust based not on rapacious practices, but on =
market share alone.=C2=A0
Hall invented a technology (and protected it with patents) to manufacture a=
 product with structurally superior unit economics in order to bring down c=
osts and both successfully compete in existing markets and create new ones.=
=C2=A0
Or take Carnegie Steel. In 1860, when Andrew Carnegie was dabbling in iron =
investments, the superior steel was so expensive to make that it was only m=
ade in small batches; the US produced [ https://substack.com/redirect/6625e=
68c-482b-4434-add2-c2f39e879fa7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] only 13,000 tons that year. But in 1872, Carnegie=
 saw the Bessemer Process in action at a plant in England, and introduced i=
t to his J. Edgar Thompson Steelworks in 1875. By the turn of the century, =
the US produced over 11 million tons of steel, and Carnegie was its largest=
 and most profitable producer.
The first ton of steel Carnegie produced cost [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/881a8325-3816-4e69-8f42-701b5519eae4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] about $56; by 1900, Carnegie was producin=
g steel at $11.50 per ton, a 72% decline. At lower prices and increased man=
ufacturing capacity, steel underpinned railroads, ships, and newly-possible=
-thanks-to-steel skyscrapers, which helped meet the growing demand for urba=
n dwellings to house an influx of immigrants.
The 1901 sale of Carnegie Steel to JP Morgan=E2=80=99s U.S. Steel for $480 =
million made Carnegie the richest man in the world and gave the newly-creat=
ed conglomerate two-thirds of the US Steel market.=C2=A0
Carnegie used a new technology, and vertically integrated around it, to man=
ufacture a product with structurally superior unit economics in order to br=
ing down costs and both successfully compete in existing markets and create=
 new ones.=C2=A0
ALCOA and Carnegie Steel took two different approaches =E2=80=93 innovation=
 and integration, respectively =E2=80=93 to achieve the same ends: driving =
down costs and increasing production.=C2=A0
As Carnegie himself put it:
Show me your cost sheets. It is more interesting to know how well and how c=
heaply you have done this thing than how much money you have made, because =
the one is a temporary result, due possibly to special conditions of trade,=
 but the other means a permanency that will go on with the works as long as=
 they last.
By structurally superior unit economics, I mean that there is something in =
the way the product is manufactured or delivered that gives the Techno-Indu=
strial a cost advantage that can=E2=80=99t easily be replicated. For ALCOA,=
 that was the patented Hall-H=C3=A9roult Process. For Carnegie Steel, it wa=
s the application of the new Bessemer Process combined with vertical integr=
ation of the supply chain and a maniacal focus on cost across the whole thi=
ng.=C2=A0
In both cases, new technology was a necessary ingredient that the companies=
 leveraged in their manufacturing processes in order to drive down costs, g=
row demand, and increase scale to drive costs down further. They didn=E2=80=
=99t just change prices, they got closer to the true cost physics of their =
products.=C2=A0
Modern Techno-Industrials can take either the ALCOA inventor route or the C=
arnegie integrator route. I=E2=80=99d argue that Solugen is an example of a=
n inventor and Anduril and Monumental Labs are integrators, although the li=
ne, in both the old examples and the new, is a little blurry. In either cas=
e, they will face enormous headwinds as they race to scale.=C2=A0
Techno-Industrial Challenges=C2=A0
Operating in the world of atoms is different than operating in the world of=
 bits.=C2=A0
In the world of bits, you don=E2=80=99t need to ask permission; in the worl=
d of atoms, you do.=C2=A0
In bits, you can pivot and iterate and ship updates and run experiments; in=
 atoms, you need to have your strategy and roadmap dialed in early.=C2=A0
In bits, you can build early products with very little capital, and increas=
ingly, you can scale with less capital; in atoms, you need large pools of c=
apital, including venture capital, but also including debt, asset-based fin=
ancing, and project financing.=C2=A0
As energy, intelligence, and dexterity get cheaper, the world of atoms will=
 come to look more like the world of bits, but it will never be as fluid as=
 the world of bits.=C2=A0
There are a few big categories of challenges that Techno-Industrials will n=
eed to face that software companies don=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
The first is that manufacturing is hard. I didn=E2=80=99t listen to the who=
le Elon Musk Joe Rogan interview [ https://substack.com/redirect/c8229e62-0=
9cc-4b3c-91df-26fc3acab435?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], but in the bit that I heard, Elon mentioned how hard =
manufacturing is roughly 100 times. Getting something to work in the lab is=
 very different than getting it to work at scale. Making one of something a=
t whatever cost is very different than repeatedly making thousands of that =
thing at a cost that looks anything like the cost in a techno-economic anal=
ysis.=C2=A0
The incumbents that Techno-Industrials will be competing with are excellent=
 at manufacturing. It=E2=80=99s what they do. The chemical giants like BASF=
 and Dow are manufacturing wonders. The concrete industry produces billions=
 of cubic meters of the product every year.=C2=A0
Relatedly, incumbents have scale and distribution. They have long-standing =
supplier and customer relationships around the world. In many cases, these =
battles will be a race to see if incumbents can get technology before Techn=
o-Industrials get scale and distribution.=C2=A0
In some cases, Techno-Industrials (the inventors) might be protected by pat=
ents, but large companies might find it economically advantageous to ignore=
 the patents and bleed poorer startups dry in court. And if not in America,=
 Chinese manufacturers will certainly run roughshod over intellectual prope=
rty and flood the market with cheaper versions of the same product. Competi=
ng in markets in which Chinese companies are unable to serve western custom=
ers is a key consideration.=C2=A0
Within America, regulations can either be helpful or harmful. Regulatory ca=
pture by incumbents is a real threat to Techno-Industrials. Lobbying effort=
s come up in every conversation with Techno-Industrial founders. Anduril fa=
mously hired more lobbyists than engineers in its first few months. Watch t=
he Bill Gurley talk [ https://substack.com/redirect/45ff3e1a-8ae7-4721-ba66=
-112cc0801077?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] again for a sober reminder.
Then, there=E2=80=99s the matter of timing. These are such big and exciting=
 opportunities that companies will attack them whether or not the economics=
 make sense quite yet, in hopes that they will when the time is right. Ther=
e=E2=80=99s a graveyard full of companies that were too early, and I suspec=
t we=E2=80=99ll see many Techno-Industrials emerge in categories that have =
scarred investors but might now make sense.=C2=A0
Finally, building a Techno-Industrial is capital intensive. These companies=
 will need to show consistent and rapid progress against their milestones i=
n order to raise the funding they need to survive and grow. As Varda=E2=80=
=99s Delian Asparouhov told me [ https://substack.com/redirect/7269a169-627=
b-4109-9646-e5c53ce5d72a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9Cdeeptech companies should begin generating rev=
enue within three years.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
There are ways to overcome these challenges, of course. Tesla and SpaceX ar=
e proof that it=E2=80=99s possible. That might mean starting at the high-en=
d of the market, where margins are higher and competition is less cutthroat=
=2E It might mean starting with a novel=
 product with a smaller market that in=
cumbents can=E2=80=99t or won=E2=80=99t build before scaling up into direct=
 competition. It might mean positioning as a climate company in order to ge=
t customer buy-in and government subsidies before translating the efficienc=
ies that come with climate-consciousness into efficiencies that lock-in hig=
her margins.=C2=A0
But have no doubt, it will be a battle. I think the prize is worth it.=C2=
=A0
Searching for Techno-Industrials
The category alternately called hard tech / deep tech / frontier tech / ato=
ms-based / American Dynamism is on fire. The things that these companies ar=
e able to do and build boggle the mind.=C2=A0
It takes a new, old way of thinking about tech companies to understand whic=
h might break through to become very large standable businesses, and this i=
s my first entry in what I suspect will be an ongoing attempt to put a fram=
ework around it.=C2=A0
While software has been all about swamping upfront fixed costs with high gr=
oss margins as revenue grows, I think the defining characteristic of succes=
sful Techno-Industrials will be whether they have a structural cost advanta=
ge.=C2=A0
That might come from an in-house invention or the integration of a number o=
f new capabilities in novel and defensible ways. In either case, if Techno-=
Industrials are to succeed, it will be because they leverage technology to =
do what technology is supposed to do: give people more and better for less.
We covered three examples =E2=80=93 Anduril, Solugen, and Monumental Labs =
=E2=80=93 taking three different approaches towards that end. Beautifully, =
there is no playbook written yet, and I suspect each Techno-Industrial will=
 forge a different path.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m on the hunt for more examples =E2=80=93 please send me your fav=
orites =E2=80=93 both to analyze and potentially to invest in. While the ch=
allenges they face will be enormous, the potential equals it.=C2=A0
For the first time in a long time, tech companies have the opportunity to r=
ebuild the world=E2=80=99s industrial base and tap into huge, existing pool=
s of revenue at higher margins than incumbents can. Assuming the same reven=
ue =E2=80=93 a safe assumption, since revenue will likely grow with lower p=
rices =E2=80=93 structurally higher margins will create more valuable compa=
nies than the incumbent comps.=C2=A0
