style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">techno-econom=
ic analyses</a><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">A skeptic would ar=
gue that we&#8217;ve heard this story before. In the 2010s, companies that =
dealt in the physical world promised better margins through technology.&#16=
0;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Companies like WeWork, Bird, and my company, Breath=
er, failed to live up to that promise.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, =
64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Ult=
imately, while they were </span><em>tech-enabled</em><span>, the technology=
 wasn&#8217;t infused into the product in such a way that they changed the =
cost physics of their industries.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64=
, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">From an=
 economic perspective, it was like squeezing a money balloon: we just shift=
ed dollars from one side to the other.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There are also =
a number of successes. DoorDash is worth $42 billion. Airbnb is worth $89 b=
illion. Uber is worth $134 billion.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64,=
 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I would argu=
e that these companies didn&#8217;t change the cost physics of their indust=
ries, either. Food is not cheaper. Travel is not cheaper. Catching a ride i=
s not cheaper.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>These companies are example=
s of what Ben Thompson famously calls </span><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
