y 1900, Carnegie was producing steel at $11.50 per ton, a 72% decline. At l=
ower prices and increased manufacturing capacity, steel underpinned railroa=
ds, ships, and newly-possible-thanks-to-steel skyscrapers, which helped mee=
t the growing demand for urban dwellings to house an influx of immigrants.<=
/span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The 1901 sale of Carnegie Steel to JP Morgan&#8=
217;s U.S. Steel for $480 million made Carnegie the richest man in the worl=
d and gave the newly-created conglomerate two-thirds of the US Steel market=
=2E&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64,=20=
64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Carnegie used a new technology, and vertically=
 integrated around it, to manufacture a product with structurally superior =
unit economics in order to bring down costs and both successfully compete i=
n existing markets and create new ones.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64,=
 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">ALCOA an=
d Carnegie Steel took two different approaches &#8211; innovation and integ=
ration, respectively &#8211; to achieve the same ends: driving down costs a=
nd increasing production.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">As Carnegie himself pu=
t it:</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px =
0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>Show me your cost =
sheets. It is more interesting to know how well and how cheaply you have do=
ne this thing than how much money you have made, because the one is a tempo=
rary result, due possibly to special conditions of trade, but the other mea=
ns a permanency that will go on with the works as long as they last.</em></=
p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>By </span><strong>structurally super=
ior unit economics</strong><span>, I mean that there is something in the wa=
y the product is manufactured or delivered that gives the Techno-Industrial=
 a cost advantage that can&#8217;t easily be replicated. For ALCOA, that wa=
s the patented Hall-H&#233;roult Process. For Carnegie Steel, it was the ap=
plication of the new Bessemer Process combined with vertical integration of=
 the supply chain and a maniacal focus on cost across the whole thing.&#160=
;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In both cases, new technology was a nec=
essary ingredient that the companies leveraged in their manufacturing proce=
sses in order to drive down costs, grow demand, and increase scale to drive=
 costs down further. They didn&#8217;t just change prices, they got closer =
to the true </span><strong>cost physics</strong><span> of their products.&#=
160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Modern Techno-Industrials can take either =
the ALCOA inventor route or the Carnegie integrator route. I&#8217;d argue =
that Solugen is an example of an inventor and Anduril and Monumental Labs a=
re integrators, although the line, in both the old examples and the new, is=
 a little blurry. In either case, they will face enormous headwinds as they=
 race to scale.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-=
