 appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family: 'SF C=
ompact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Hel=
vetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI=
 Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margi=
n: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Techno-Industrial Challeng=
es</strong><span>&#160;</span></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Operating in the world=
 of atoms is different than operating in the world of bits.&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">In the world of bits, you don&#8217;t need to ask permission; i=
n the world of atoms, you do.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In bits, you can p=
ivot and iterate and ship updates and run experiments; in atoms, you need t=
o have your strategy and roadmap dialed in early.&#160;</p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">In bits, you can build early products with very little capital, and incre=
asingly, you can scale with less capital; in atoms, you need large pools of=
 capital, including venture capital, but also including debt, asset-based f=
inancing, and project financing.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>As energy=
, intelligence, and dexterity get cheaper, the world of atoms will come to =
look </span><em>more </em><span>like the world of bits, but it will never b=
e as fluid as the world of bits.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64,=
 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There ar=
e a few big categories of challenges that Techno-Industrials will need to f=
ace that software companies don&#8217;t.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64=
, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>T=
he first is that </span><strong>manufacturing is hard</strong><span>. I did=
n&#8217;t listen to the whole </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redire=
ct/c8229e62-09cc-4b3c-91df-26fc3acab435?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-=
decoration: underline;">Elon Musk Joe Rogan interview</a><span>, but in the=
 bit that I heard, Elon mentioned how hard manufacturing is roughly 100 tim=
es. Getting something to work in the lab is very different than getting it =
to work at scale. Making one of something at whatever cost is very differen=
t than repeatedly making thousands of that thing at a cost that looks anyth=
ing like the cost in a techno-economic analysis.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">The incumbents that Techno-Industrials will be competing with are=
 excellent at manufacturing. It&#8217;s what they do. The chemical giants l=
ike BASF and Dow are manufacturing wonders. The concrete industry produces =
billions of cubic meters of the product every year.&#160;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;"><span>Relatedly, </span><strong>incumbents have scale</strong><span> </=
span><strong>and distribution. </strong><span>They have long-standing suppl=
ier and customer relationships around the world. In many cases, these battl=
es will be a race to see if incumbents can get technology before Techno-Ind=
ustrials get scale and distribution.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><spa=
n>In some cases, Techno-Industrials (the inventors) might be protected by <=
/span><strong>patents</strong><span>, but large companies might find it eco=
nomically advantageous to ignore the patents and bleed poorer startups dry =
in court. And if not in America, Chinese manufacturers will certainly run r=
oughshod over intellectual property and flood the market with cheaper versi=
ons of the same product. Competing in markets in which Chinese companies ar=
e unable to serve western customers is a key consideration.&#160;</span></p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Within America, regulations can either be helpful =
or harmful. </span><strong>Regulatory capture</strong><span> by incumbents =
is a real threat to Techno-Industrials. Lobbying efforts come up in every c=
onversation with Techno-Industrial founders. Anduril famously hired more lo=
bbyists than engineers in its first few months. Watch </span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/45ff3e1a-8ae7-4721-ba66-112cc0801077?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color=
: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">the Bill Gurley talk</a><sp=
an> again for a sober reminder.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Then, the=
re&#8217;s the matter of </span><strong>timing</strong><span>. These are su=
ch big and exciting opportunities that companies will attack them whether o=
r not the economics make sense quite yet, in hopes that they will when the =
time is right. There&#8217;s a graveyard full of companies that were too ea=
rly, and I suspect we&#8217;ll see many Techno-Industrials emerge in catego=
ries that have scarred investors but might now make sense.&#160;</span></p>=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Finally, building a Techno-Industrial is </span><st=
rong>capital intensive</strong><span>. These companies will need to show co=
nsistent and rapid progress against their milestones in order to raise the =
funding they need to survive and grow. As Varda&#8217;s Delian Asparouhov <=
/span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/7269a169-627b-4109-9646-e5c5=
3ce5d72a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">told me=
</a><span>, &#8220;deeptech companies should begin generating revenue withi=
n three years.&#8221;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There are ways to o=
vercome these challenges, of course. Tesla and SpaceX are proof that it&#82=
17;s possible. That might mean starting at the high-end of the market, wher=
e margins are higher and competition is less cutthroat. It might mean start=
ing with a novel product with a smaller market that incumbents can&#8217;t =
or won&#8217;t build before scaling up into direct competition. It might me=
an positioning as a climate company in order to get customer buy-in and gov=
ernment subsidies before translating the efficiencies that come with climat=
e-consciousness into efficiencies that lock-in higher margins.&#160;</p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">But have no doubt, it will be a battle. I think the prize is=
 worth it.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-a=
ppearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webki=
t-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appe=
arance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family: 'SF Compac=
t Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetic=
a, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symb=
ol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1e=
m 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Searching for Techno-Industrial=
s</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The category alternately called hard tech =
/ deep tech / frontier tech / atoms-based / American Dynamism is on fire. T=
he things that these companies are able to do and build boggle the mind.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It takes a new, old way of thinking about tech com=
panies to understand which might break through to become very large standab=
le businesses, and this is my first entry in what I suspect will be an ongo=
ing attempt to put a framework around it.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(6=
4, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>=
While software has been all about swamping upfront fixed costs with high gr=
oss margins as </span><strong>revenue</strong><span> grows, I think the def=
ining characteristic of successful Techno-Industrials will be whether they =
have a structural </span><strong>cost</strong><span> advantage.&#160;</span=
></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That might come from an in-house </span><stron=
g>invention</strong><span> or the </span><strong>integration</strong><span>=
 of a number of new capabilities in novel and defensible ways. In either ca=
se, if Techno-Industrials are to succeed, it will be because they leverage =
technology to do what technology is supposed to do: </span><strong>give peo=
ple more and better for less.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">We covered thre=
e examples &#8211; Anduril, Solugen, and Monumental Labs &#8211; taking thr=
ee different approaches towards that end. Beautifully, there is no playbook=
 written yet, and I suspect each Techno-Industrial will forge a different p=
ath.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I&#8217;m on the hunt for more examples &#8=
211; please send me your favorites &#8211; both to analyze and potentially =
to invest in. While the challenges they face will be enormous, the potentia=
l equals it.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">For the first time in a long time, =
tech companies have the opportunity to rebuild the world&#8217;s industrial=
 base and tap into huge, existing pools of revenue at higher margins than i=
ncumbents can. Assuming the same revenue &#8211; a safe assumption, since r=
evenue will likely grow with lower prices &#8211; structurally higher margi=
ns will create more valuable companies than the incumbent comps.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;">I suspect that in a decade or two, there will be dozens of=
 trillion-dollar companies, and my bet is that many of them will be Techno-=
Industrials.</p><div style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;"><hr styl=
e=3D"background: #e0e0e0; border: none; height: 1px; margin: 32px 0; paddin=
